<subSubSection id="C36B654CFFC9F719E941FBE7FEE1FA25" pageId="1" pageNumber="596" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BCE36C7FFC9F719E941FBE7FEE1FA25" blockId="1.[113,1089,1122,1595]" pageId="1" pageNumber="596">
<emphasis id="B905EAD5FFC9F719E941FBE7FF74FBC4" bold="true" box="[113,230,1122,1146]" pageId="1" pageNumber="596">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The new species is superficially similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C714D44FFC9F719EB89FBE1FF34FB24" authority="Cockerell, 1896" authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1896" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Perdita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="596" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stottleri" subGenus="Perdita">
<emphasis id="B905EAD5FFC9F719EB89FBE1FC9AFBC5" box="[697,776,1124,1147]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="596">Perdita</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="B905EAD5FFC9F719EA28FBE1FCF5FBC5" box="[792,871,1124,1147]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="596">Perdita</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="B905EAD5FFC9F719EA48FBE1FC59FBC5" box="[888,971,1124,1147]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="596">stottleri</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFE04B36FFC9F719EAE2FBE6FF34FB24" author="COCKERELL T. D. A." pageId="1" pageNumber="596" pagination="201 - 207" refId="ref2682" refString="COCKERELL T. D. A. 1896: New species of insects taken on a trip from the Mesilla Valley to the Sacramento Mts., New Mexico. Journal of the New York Entomological Society 4: 201 - 207." type="journal article" year="1896">Cockerell, 1896</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and will run to this species in TIMBERLAKE’ s (1958) key to the 
<emphasis id="B905EAD5FFC9F719EA06FB01FC10FB25" box="[822,898,1156,1179]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="596">zonalis</emphasis>
species group but differs in its facial maculation (
<figureCitation id="134A2A42FFC9F719E8F6FB26FD9AFB05" box="[454,520,1187,1211]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[112,151,1281,1300]" captionTargetBox="[124,1077,224,1267]" captionTargetId="figure-91@3.[124,1077,219,1268]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 2–5. Perdita (Perdita) islacabritosensis sp. nov., male holotype: 2 – dorsal habitus; 3 – facial view; 4 – dorsal detail of base of propodeum; 5 – dorsal view of metasoma." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5332755" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5332755/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="596">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
; 
<emphasis id="B905EAD5FFC9F719EB26FB21FDBBFB05" box="[534,553,1188,1211]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="596">cf</emphasis>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE04B36FFC9F719EB08FB26FD78FB04" author="COCKERELL T. D. A." box="[568,746,1186,1211]" pageId="1" pageNumber="596" pagination="201 - 207" refId="ref2682" refString="COCKERELL T. D. A. 1896: New species of insects taken on a trip from the Mesilla Valley to the Sacramento Mts., New Mexico. Journal of the New York Entomological Society 4: 201 - 207." type="journal article" year="1896">COCKERELL 1896</bibRefCitation>
) and its noticeably smaller size (length around 
<quantity id="4C899B22FFC9F719E824FB47FEC0FB64" box="[276,338,1218,1242]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="596" unit="mm" value="6.0">6 mm</quantity>
in 
<taxonomicName id="4C714D44FFC9F719E844FB41FE77FB65" authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1896" box="[372,485,1219,1243]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Perdita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="596" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stottleri">
<emphasis id="B905EAD5FFC9F719E844FB41FE16FB65" box="[372,388,1220,1243]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="596">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B905EAD5FFC9F719E8A2FB41FE77FB65" box="[402,485,1220,1243]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="596">stottleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
vs. about 
<quantity id="4C899B22FFC9F719EB63FB47FD36FB64" box="[595,676,1218,1242]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" pageId="1" pageNumber="596" unit="mm" value="4.5">4.5 mm</quantity>
in the new species). The species share the presence of yellow anteriorly on the mesosternum and completely yellow face below the level of the antennae, the finely and even faintly imbricate (= evanescent tessellation 
<emphasis id="B905EAD5FFC9F719E941FAA1FF3EFA85" box="[113,172,1316,1339]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="596">sensu</emphasis>
Timberlake) integument of the mesoscutum, and the shorter mandibles which extend at most to the far side of the proboscidial fossa. Such characters are perhaps not indicative of genealogical relationship and considerable phylogenetic work is needed in 
<taxonomicName id="4C714D44FFC9F719EABBFAE1FBD3FAC5" authority="(Perdita)" box="[907,1089,1379,1403]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Perdita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="596" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Perdita">
<emphasis id="B905EAD5FFC9F719EABBFAE1FC48FAC5" box="[907,986,1380,1403]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="596">Perdita</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="B905EAD5FFC9F719EAD9FAE1FBAAFAC5" box="[1001,1080,1380,1403]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="596">Perdita</emphasis>
)
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis id="B905EAD5FFC9F719E94AFA01FF34FA25" box="[122,166,1412,1435]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="596">vide</emphasis>
Discussion, 
<emphasis id="B905EAD5FFC9F719E800FA01FEF6FA25" box="[304,356,1412,1435]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="596">infra</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36B654CFFC9F71CE941FA27FE14FD2D" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="599" pageId="1" pageNumber="596" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BCE36C7FFC9F71AE941FA27FE1BFB04" blockId="1.[113,1089,1122,1595]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1127,1122,1594]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="597" pageId="1" pageNumber="596">
<emphasis id="B905EAD5FFC9F719E941FA27FED0FA05" bold="true" box="[113,322,1442,1467]" pageId="1" pageNumber="596">
Description. 
<emphasis id="B905EAD5FFC9F719E833FA27FEA9FA05" bold="true" box="[259,315,1442,1467]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="596">Male</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Total body length 
<quantity id="4C899B22FFC9F719EB3CFA26FDF9FA04" box="[524,619,1443,1467]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.42" pageId="1" pageNumber="596" unit="mm" value="4.42">4.42 mm</quantity>
(
<quantity id="4C899B22FFC9F719EB4AFA27FD4DFA05" box="[634,735,1442,1467]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.25" pageId="1" pageNumber="596" unit="mm" value="4.25">4.25 mm</quantity>
); forewing length 
<quantity id="4C899B22FFC9F719EA93FA26FB93FA04" box="[931,1025,1443,1467]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.92" pageId="1" pageNumber="596" unit="mm" value="2.92">2.92 mm</quantity>
(
<quantity id="4C899B22FFC9F719ED20FA26FF0DFA65" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.88" pageId="1" pageNumber="596" unit="mm" value="2.88">2.88 mm</quantity>
). Head wider than long, length 
<quantity id="4C899B22FFC9F719E8C5FA46FDC6FA64" box="[501,596,1475,1499]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.07" pageId="1" pageNumber="596" unit="mm" value="1.07">1.07 mm</quantity>
(
<quantity id="4C899B22FFC9F719EB54FA46FD5BFA65" box="[612,713,1475,1499]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.01" pageId="1" pageNumber="596" unit="mm" value="1.01">1.01 mm</quantity>
), width 
<quantity id="4C899B22FFC9F719EA11FA47FC13FA64" box="[801,897,1474,1498]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.35" pageId="1" pageNumber="596" unit="mm" value="1.35">1.35 mm</quantity>
(
<quantity id="4C899B22FFC9F719EAA1FA46FC64FA65" box="[913,1014,1475,1499]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.29" pageId="1" pageNumber="596" unit="mm" value="1.29">1.29 mm</quantity>
); mandible simple, not elongate or falcate, extending at most to far margin of proboscidial fossa when closed; gena narrower than compound eye; facial fovea weakly impressed, a little less than one-half median ocellar diameter in width, about twice as long as wide. Pronotum with medial, transverse ridge running laterally into lateral grooves which curve posteriorly anterior of pronotal lobe. Intertegular distance 
<quantity id="4C899B22FFCAF71AEBBEFB07FD63FB24" box="[654,753,1154,1178]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.7" pageId="2" pageNumber="597" unit="mm" value="0.97">0.97 mm</quantity>
. Pygidial plate tapering apically to acutely-rounded point.
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF0E664FFFCAF71AE9A7FC7CFCE8FBB2" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5332751" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5332751" box="[151,890,1017,1036]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5332751/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="597" startId="2.[151,182,1017,1036]" targetBox="[189,1083,238,990]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph id="8BCE36C7FFCAF71AE9A7FC7CFCE8FBB2" blockId="2.[151,890,1017,1036]" box="[151,890,1017,1036]" pageId="2" pageNumber="597">
Fig. 1. Lateral habitus of holotype male of 
<taxonomicName id="4C714D44FFCAF71AEB3BFC7FFCA3FBB2" authority="Ascher &amp; Engel, 2012" authorityName="Ascher &amp; Engel" authorityYear="2012" box="[523,817,1017,1036]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Perdita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="597" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="islacabritosensis" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Perdita">
<emphasis id="B905EAD5FFCAF71AEB3BFC7FFDD8FBB2" box="[523,586,1018,1036]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="597">Perdita</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="B905EAD5FFCAF71AEB66FC7FFD07FBB2" box="[598,661,1018,1036]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="597">Perdita</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="B905EAD5FFCAF71AEB92FC7FFCA3FBB2" box="[674,817,1018,1036]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="597">islacabritosensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A23657AEFFCAF71AEA07FC7CFCE8FBB2" box="[823,890,1017,1036]" pageId="2" pageNumber="597" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8BCE36C7FFCAF71AE985FB46FD5BF984" blockId="2.[151,1127,1122,1594]" pageId="2" pageNumber="597">
Integument of head and mesosoma gently and finely imbricate (= evanescent tessellation 
<emphasis id="B905EAD5FFCAF71AE9A7FB66FF40FB44" box="[151,210,1251,1274]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="597">sensu</emphasis>
Timberlake) (consistent with 
<emphasis id="B905EAD5FFCAF71AEB26FB66FDF0FB44" box="[534,610,1251,1274]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="597">zonalis</emphasis>
group); labrum impunctate; clypeus impunctate medially otherwise with small, shallow, and faint punctures separated by 1–2 times a puncture width; supraclypeal area impunctate; face with small, shallow, and faint (only visible under raking light) punctures separated by 1–3 times a puncture width; vertex sculptured as on face, integument shiny; gena as on vertex except punctures more sparse. Pronotum impunctate; mesoscutum with small, shallow, faint punctures separated by 1.5–3.5 times a puncture width; mesoscutellum and metanotum as on mesoscutum although punctures separated by 1–2.5 times a puncture width and imbrication stronger on metanotum; mesepisternum with small, shallow, and faint punctures separated by 2–5 times a puncture width; metepisternum impunctate; basal area of propodeum impunctate (
<figureCitation id="134A2A42FFCAF71AEB87F987FD69F9A4" box="[695,763,1538,1562]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[112,151,1281,1300]" captionTargetBox="[124,1077,224,1267]" captionTargetId="figure-91@3.[124,1077,219,1268]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 2–5. Perdita (Perdita) islacabritosensis sp. nov., male holotype: 2 – dorsal habitus; 3 – facial view; 4 – dorsal detail of base of propodeum; 5 – dorsal view of metasoma." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5332755" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5332755/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="597">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
); lateral and posterior surfaces of propodeum impunctate. Metasoma faintly imbricate.
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF0E664FFFCBF71BE940FA84FDFBFA8E" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5332755" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5332755" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5332755/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="598" startId="3.[112,151,1281,1300]" targetBox="[124,1077,224,1267]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph id="8BCE36C7FFCBF71BE940FA84FDFBFA8E" blockId="3.[112,1088,1281,1328]" pageId="3" pageNumber="598">
Figs. 2–5. 
<taxonomicName id="4C714D44FFCBF71BE9FEFA86FE61FAAB" authority="Ascher &amp; Engel, 2012" authorityName="Ascher &amp; Engel" authorityYear="2012" box="[206,499,1282,1301]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Perdita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="598" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="islacabritosensis" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Perdita">
<emphasis id="B905EAD5FFCBF71BE9FEFA86FE9FFAAB" box="[206,269,1283,1301]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="598">Perdita</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="B905EAD5FFCBF71BE829FA86FECAFAAB" box="[281,344,1283,1301]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="598">Perdita</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="B905EAD5FFCBF71BE854FA86FE61FAAB" box="[356,499,1283,1301]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="598">islacabritosensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A23657AEFFCBF71BE8C8FA87FDA9FAAB" box="[504,571,1282,1301]" pageId="3" pageNumber="598" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, male holotype: 2 – dorsal habitus; 3 – facial view; 4 – dorsal detail of base of propodeum; 5 – dorsal view of metasoma.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8BCE36C7FFCBF71CE9A0FAFEFCFBFDED" blockId="3.[113,1089,1403,1555]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1127,219,916]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="599" pageId="3" pageNumber="598">
Head dark brown with a blue-green tint except yellow on mandible (red at apex), labrum, clypeus, most of face below level of ocelli as depicted in 
<figureCitation id="134A2A42FFCBF71BEBD3FA1EFCB0FA0D" box="[739,802,1435,1459]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[112,151,1281,1300]" captionTargetBox="[124,1077,224,1267]" captionTargetId="figure-91@3.[124,1077,219,1268]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 2–5. Perdita (Perdita) islacabritosensis sp. nov., male holotype: 2 – dorsal habitus; 3 – facial view; 4 – dorsal detail of base of propodeum; 5 – dorsal view of metasoma." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5332755" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5332755/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="598">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
(consistent with the 
<emphasis id="B905EAD5FFCBF71BED35FA19FF18FA6D" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="598">zonalis</emphasis>
group), and antenna except brown on dorsum of pedicel, flagellomeres I–IV, less so on flagellomeres V–VII, and dorsobasally on flagellomere VIII (
<figureCitation id="134A2A42FFCBF71BEBCDFA5EFCADFA4D" box="[765,831,1499,1523]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[112,151,1281,1300]" captionTargetBox="[124,1077,224,1267]" captionTargetId="figure-91@3.[124,1077,219,1268]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 2–5. Perdita (Perdita) islacabritosensis sp. nov., male holotype: 2 – dorsal habitus; 3 – facial view; 4 – dorsal detail of base of propodeum; 5 – dorsal view of metasoma." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5332755" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5332755/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="598">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Pronotum yellow with broad transverse band of dark brown with blue-green tint medially (
<figureCitation id="134A2A42FFCBF71BEA06FA7EFCE4F9AD" box="[822,886,1531,1555]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[112,151,1281,1300]" captionTargetBox="[124,1077,224,1267]" captionTargetId="figure-91@3.[124,1077,219,1268]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 2–5. Perdita (Perdita) islacabritosensis sp. nov., male holotype: 2 – dorsal habitus; 3 – facial view; 4 – dorsal detail of base of propodeum; 5 – dorsal view of metasoma." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5332755" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5332755/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="598">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), laterally band not reaching to ventral margin; propleura yellow; mesoscutum dark brown with blue-green tints; tegula light translucent yellow; mesoscutellum and metanotum as on mesoscutum; pleura dark brown with blue-green tints except yellow anteriorly on mesepisternum as depicted in 
<figureCitation id="134A2A42FFCCF71CE9A7FEBEFF44FEEA" box="[151,214,315,340]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[151,182,1017,1036]" captionTargetBox="[189,1083,238,990]" captionTargetId="figure-181@2.[174,1103,219,1004]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Lateral habitus of holotype male of Perdita (Perdita) islacabritosensis sp. nov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5332751" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5332751/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="599">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
; propodeum dark brown with blue-green tint. Legs yellow except brown on posterior surface of metafemur, outer surface of metatibia, and dark brown dorsally on metacoxa. Wing membranes hyaline and clear; veins light yellow brown. Metasomal terga dark brown except extensively marked with yellow to create banded appearance (consistent with the 
<emphasis id="B905EAD5FFCCF71CED2BFE18FBF5FE0A" box="[1051,1127,413,436]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="599">zonalis</emphasis>
group); tergum I with yellow laterally and forming a broad band across disc at bend between anterior- and dorsal-facing surfaces, band of yellow only slightly narrower than apical margin of dark brown, anteromedially notched; tergum II–V each with broad medial band of yellow across disc, bands of terga II–IV broader than apical dark brown areas (
<figureCitation id="134A2A42FFCCF71CEAB2FD9EFC50FD8D" box="[898,962,539,563]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[112,151,1281,1300]" captionTargetBox="[124,1077,224,1267]" captionTargetId="figure-91@3.[124,1077,219,1268]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 2–5. Perdita (Perdita) islacabritosensis sp. nov., male holotype: 2 – dorsal habitus; 3 – facial view; 4 – dorsal detail of base of propodeum; 5 – dorsal view of metasoma." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5332755" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5332755/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="599">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
); pygidial plate brown; sterna yellow except extreme base of sternum I dark brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCE36C7FFCCF71CE985FDDEFBB6FDCD" blockId="4.[151,1127,219,916]" box="[181,1060,603,628]" pageId="4" pageNumber="599">
Pubescence typical for males of subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="4C714D44FFCCF71CEB49FDD8FD5AFDCA" authorityName="Smith" authorityYear="1853" box="[633,712,605,628]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Perdita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="599" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B905EAD5FFCCF71CEB49FDD8FD5AFDCA" box="[633,712,605,628]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="599">Perdita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and generally white throughout.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCE36C7FFCCF71CE985FDFFFE14FD2D" blockId="4.[151,1127,219,916]" box="[181,390,634,660]" pageId="4" pageNumber="599">
<emphasis id="B905EAD5FFCCF71CE985FDFFFE9DFD2A" bold="true" box="[181,271,634,660]" pageId="4" pageNumber="599">
<emphasis id="B905EAD5FFCCF71CE985FDFFFE9AFD2D" bold="true" box="[181,264,634,659]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="599">Female</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36B654CFFCCF71CE9A7FD19FF6DFD6D" pageId="4" pageNumber="599" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BCE36C7FFCCF71CE9A7FD19FF6DFD6D" blockId="4.[151,1127,219,916]" pageId="4" pageNumber="599">
<emphasis id="B905EAD5FFCCF71CE9A7FD19FE8AFD0A" bold="true" box="[151,280,668,692]" pageId="4" pageNumber="599">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is taken from the 
<typeStatus id="54CA8865FFCCF71CEBF2FD19FD62FD0A" box="[706,752,668,692]" pageId="4" pageNumber="599">type</typeStatus>
locality, 
<collectingCountry id="F3667657FFCCF71CEA67FD1EFCECFD0D" box="[855,894,667,691]" name="Iceland" pageId="4" pageNumber="599">Isla</collectingCountry>
Cabritos, 
<collectingCountry id="F3667657FFCCF71CEAC0FD1EFF69FD6D" name="Dominican Republic" pageId="4" pageNumber="599">Dominican Republic</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36B654CFFCCF71CE9A7FD5EFEB9FC2A" pageId="4" pageNumber="599" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BCE36C7FFCCF71CE9A7FD5EFEB9FC2A" blockId="4.[151,1127,219,916]" pageId="4" pageNumber="599">
<emphasis id="B905EAD5FFCCF71CE9A7FD5EFE88FD4D" bold="true" box="[151,282,731,755]" pageId="4" pageNumber="599">Comments.</emphasis>
An attempt was made to dissect the material but after considerable time in a humidification chamber the apical metasomal segments were unrelenting and we opted to refrain from further manipulation less the specimen become damaged. It is greatly hoped that extensive sampling of bees in 
<collectingCountry id="F3667657FFCCF71CE8E4FCBEFDE0FCED" box="[468,626,827,851]" name="Dominican Republic" pageId="4" pageNumber="599">the Dominican</collectingCountry>
Republic might bring forth additional material, including females, so that the species can be more fully characterized and compared with its congeners.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
